</head>


<body>

  <!-- ===================== ZONE 1 — HERO ===================== -->
  <section class="hero" data-screen-label="Hero">
    <div class="container wrap">
      <div class="copy">
        <div class="eyebrow"><span class="k">Written by an FMF Navy Corpsman</span><span class="rule"></span></div>
        <h1>A Corpsman's Guide to Listening to Your Nervous System.</h1>
        <p class="sub">The war within finally has a field manual.</p>
        <p class="body">Six pillars. Seven tools. 30 days. <b>A field-tested nervous system protocol created by a Navy corpsman who spent 18 years struggling with PTSD.</b> $27.</p>
        <div class="cta-row">
          <a href="#offer" class="btn btn-primary">Get the Manual — $27</a>
          <a href="#letter" class="btn btn-ghost">Read the Letter from Bobby</a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="book"><img src="/images/nsfm-cover.png" alt="The Nervous System Field Manual"></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="trust">
    <div class="container row">
      <div class="item"><b>★</b>FMF Navy Corpsman</div>
      <div class="item"><b>✦</b>OEF Veteran</div>
      <div class="item"><b>▮</b>Built from 18 Years of Field Testing</div>
      <div class="item"><b>✚</b>PTSD Recovery Survivor</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ===================== ZONE 2 — THE MIRROR ===================== -->
  <section class="sec mirror" data-screen-label="The Mirror">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="sec-head textcol">
        <div class="eyebrow"><span class="k">You Already Know This Feeling</span></div>
        <h2 class="h2">You've Done Everything Right on Paper.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="textcol">
        <p class="lead">You showed up to the appointments. You took the medications they offered and waited six weeks to find out they flattened everything without fixing anything. You sat in the chair, told the story again, gained the insight, and walked out with the same body you walked in with — still braced, still scanning, still wired for a threat that isn't there anymore.</p>
        <p class="lead">You've cycled through enough providers that you've stopped expecting anything new. And somewhere underneath the exhaustion, you've started to wonder if this is just who you are now — if something in you got permanently altered, and the rest of your life is just managing it.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="callout textcol">
        <span class="tag">The Almost Moment</span>
        <p>In 2023 you finally got a diagnosis — a real one, with structure and language that fit — and for about a week it felt like the beginning of something, until you realized a name for the weight doesn't make it lighter.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="emph textcol">
        <p><span class="hl">The diagnosis isn't wrong. The approach is.</span> Talk therapy and medication are top-down interventions — they work through the thinking mind, and your nervous system doesn't live there. Your nervous system isn't broken. It was <strong>trained</strong>. Precisely, effectively, and successfully trained — for an environment that no longer exists. That's not a defect. That's a mismatch. And mismatches can be corrected.</p>
      </div>

      <p class="feel-label">Here's what correcting it actually feels like</p>
      <ul class="feel-list">
        <li><span class="mk">→</span><span>Waking up without running a threat assessment of your own bedroom before your feet hit the floor.</span></li>
        <li><span class="mk">→</span><span>Sitting in a crowded room without every exit already mapped and every person already categorized.</span></li>
        <li><span class="mk">→</span><span>Feeling your shoulders drop — not because you told yourself to relax, but because your system actually stopped bracing.</span></li>
        <li><span class="mk">→</span><span>Having a hard conversation without your body treating it like a contact engagement.</span></li>
        <li><span class="mk">→</span><span>Sleeping through a noise that isn't a threat, because your nervous system finally knows the difference.</span></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===================== ZONE 3 — THE MECHANISM ===================== -->
  <section class="sec panel mech" data-screen-label="The Protocol">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="sec-head textcol">
        <div class="eyebrow"><span class="k">The Protocol</span><span class="rule"></span></div>
        <h2 class="h2">Six Pillars. Seven Tools. Thirty Days.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="textcol">
        <p class="lead">While everyone else tries to reach the nervous system through the mind — through reflection, reframing, and cognitive insight — we go straight to the body, because <strong>the nervous system processes sensation before it processes language</strong>, and you cannot think your way out of a state your body is still physically holding.</p>
        <p class="lead">That's not a philosophy. It's physiology. And it's exactly why the Nervous System Regulation Protocol exists.</p>
        <p class="lead">Everything named above — the cycling, the failed protocols, the 2 a.m. body that won't stand down, the diagnosis that explained everything and changed nothing — points to the same gap: nobody ever gave you tools that work at the level where the activation actually lives. This is the direct answer to that gap. <strong>Not a framework for understanding your trauma. A working toolkit for regulating the system that's been carrying it.</strong></p>
      </div>

      <p class="phases-label">The Three Phases</p>
      <div class="phases">
        <div class="phase">
          <div class="no">01</div>
          <div class="ph-tag">Phase 1</div>
          <h3>Contact</h3>
          <p>You prove to yourself on <b>Day 1</b> that your nervous system can be reached — using the 90-Second Reset, a single tool that produces a measurable physiological shift before you've read anything else. Contact first. Theory after.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="phase">
          <div class="no">02</div>
          <div class="ph-tag">Phase 2</div>
          <h3>Regulation</h3>
          <p>You work through <b>six structured pillars</b> that build your capacity to recognize activation states and move through them deliberately — so you're no longer at the mercy of a system that doesn't know the mission ended.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="phase">
          <div class="no">03</div>
          <div class="ph-tag">Phase 3</div>
          <h3>Integration</h3>
          <p>You build a repeatable daily practice from the <b>seven tools</b> — one that travels with you, requires no appointment, and doesn't depend on someone else being in the room.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===================== ZONE 4 — PROOF & FILTER ===================== -->
  <section class="sec" data-screen-label="Proof &amp; Filter">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="sec-head textcol">
        <div class="eyebrow"><span class="k">What's Verifiable</span><span class="rule"></span></div>
        <h2 class="h2">Built on Documented Research. Proven on Day 1.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="vbox">
        <p>No specific client outcome numbers are published on this page. What <strong>is</strong> verifiable: the 90-Second Reset is drawn from peer-reviewed polyvagal and somatic research, and the protocol is built on tools with documented clinical application — <strong>not proprietary theory</strong>. Day 1 produces a measurable shift or the guarantee activates. That's the proof structure here.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="cols">
        <div class="col yes">
          <h4><span class="ic">✓</span>This Is For You If</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><span class="m">✓</span><span>You separated from service and your body still hasn't — you're home but you're not present, and you've been trying to explain that gap to people who've never felt it.</span></li>
            <li><span class="m">✓</span><span>You've been through the VA or private care rotation — diagnosis, medication, referral, repeat — and you're still carrying the same weight you walked in with.</span></li>
            <li><span class="m">✓</span><span>You know what hypervigilance feels like from the inside — not as a clinical term, but as a full-time job your body never clocks out of.</span></li>
            <li><span class="m">✓</span><span>You got a diagnosis that named it correctly but didn't change it, and you're still looking for the part where something actually shifts.</span></li>
            <li><span class="m">✓</span><span>You're functional — still standing, still working, still showing up — but you're exhausted by the cost of holding it together, and you know the current approach isn't it.</span></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="col no">
          <h4><span class="ic">✕</span>This Is Not For You If</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><span class="m">✕</span><span>You are currently in crisis and need immediate clinical intervention — this is not that, and it is not a substitute for it.</span></li>
            <li><span class="m">✕</span><span>You are looking for a licensed mental health treatment program — this is a self-directed somatic toolkit, not clinical care.</span></li>
            <li><span class="m">✕</span><span>You want a passive read that explains your nervous system without asking you to use the tools.</span></li>
            <li><span class="m">✕</span><span>You are unwilling to work directly with physical sensation — this protocol operates at the body level, and that is non-negotiable.</span></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="founder" id="letter">
        <p>I didn't build this from a case study or a certification alone. I built it because I was the person cycling through the appointments, collecting the diagnoses, and leaving every session with the same body I brought in. What I eventually realized wasn't a breakthrough insight — it was a missing layer: nobody had ever worked with me at the level where the activation actually lived. What I built is the toolkit I couldn't find when I needed it.</p>
        <span class="sig">— Bobby L. Harris, FMF Navy Corpsman</span>
      </div>
    </div>
